# Advanced Science O/X
> Deeper physics, chemistry, and biology
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.science.advanced/

According to Einstein's equation E=mc², mass and energy are equivalent and can be converted into each other. | O | E=mc² expresses the equivalence of mass and energy, a cornerstone of modern physics.
The speed of light in a vacuum is approximately 300,000 kilometers per second. | O | Light travels at about 299,792 km/s in a vacuum.
An atom's chemical identity is determined by its number of neutrons. | X | An element is defined by its number of protons (atomic number), not neutrons.
DNA base pairing follows the rule that adenine pairs with thymine and guanine pairs with cytosine. | O | In DNA, A pairs with T and G pairs with C via complementary base pairing.
Absolute zero (0 kelvin) is the lowest possible temperature on the thermodynamic scale. | O | Absolute zero is the theoretical lower limit of temperature, about -273.15°C.
Enzymes are biological catalysts that lower the activation energy of chemical reactions. | O | Enzymes speed up reactions by lowering activation energy and are not consumed in the process.
Sound can travel through the vacuum of outer space just like light. | X | Sound needs a medium (like air) to travel and cannot propagate through a vacuum; light can.
The mitochondria are often described as the powerhouse of the cell because they produce ATP. | O | Mitochondria generate ATP through cellular respiration, powering the cell.
Which subatomic particle carries a negative electric charge? | 1)Electron 2)Proton 3)Neutron 4)Photon | 1 | Electrons carry a negative charge; protons are positive and neutrons are neutral.
How many chromosomes are in a normal human body (somatic) cell? | 1)46 2)23 3)48 4)44 | 1 | Human somatic cells have 23 pairs, for a total of 46 chromosomes.
Q: What gas do plants absorb from the air and use during photosynthesis? (name the gas) | A: carbon dioxide;co2;co₂ | Plants absorb carbon dioxide and, using sunlight, produce glucose and release oxygen.
Q: What is the chemical symbol for water? (formula) | A: h2o;h₂o | Water is made of two hydrogen atoms and one oxygen atom, written H2O.
